Lazy evaluation, in depth.

The rule is simple, but here is the reference to keep in your head when you read other people's code.

Transformations are lazy. They append to the plan and return another dataframe. Select, filter, with-column, group-by, join, order-by — all transformations.

Actions are eager. They trigger execution and return a value, a file, or printed output. Show, count, collect, take, first, write — all actions.

Because evaluation is lazy, Spark gets room to be clever before any data moves.

It can push filters early, so a filter you wrote at the very end of the chain may actually execute right next to the data scan. That means less data flows through the pipeline.

It can prune projections, dropping columns you never reference before it even reads them.

It can fuse operations, collapsing several narrow transformations into one tight loop. That is whole-stage code generation, which we reach three sections from now.

And it can skip everything. If you define transformations but never call an action, no work runs at all.

Every one of these wins is possible only because Spark waited.
